	<div class="a-column " id="a-col">
	<div id="content" class="hfeed">
	<article class="post-621155 post type-post status-publish hentry category-deal-professor category-legal category-media category-mergers-acquisitions category-technology category-telecommunications tag-antitrust-laws-and-competition-issues tag-cable-television tag-computers-and-the-internet tag-mergers-acquisitions-and-divestitures tag-telephones-and-telecommunications des-antitrust-laws-and-competition-issues des-cable-television des-computers-and-the-internet des-mergers-acquisitions-and-divestitures des-telephones-and-telecommunications news_keywords-cable-television-2 news_keywords-competition-law news_keywords-computers-and-the-internet news_keywords-mergers-and-acquistions news_keywords-telecommunication" id="post-621155">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
			<span class="kicker"><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/legal/">Legal/Regulatory</a> | <a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/columnists/deal-professor/">Deal Professor</a></span>		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Changing Old Antitrust Thinking for a New Gilded Age</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Steven Davidoff Solomon			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-07-23T00:56:22+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">July 22, 2014 8:56 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">July 22, 2014 8:56 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/22/changing-old-antitrust-thinking-for-a-new-gilded-age/" data-title="Changing Old Antitrust Thinking for a New Gilded Age" data-description="Industry-consolidating acquisitions are all the rage, creating huge corporations similar to the trusts of a century ago, but different enough to require policy that considers effects beyond competition, Steven Davidoff Solomon writes in the Deal Professor column.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/23/business/dbpix-dealprof/dbpix-dealprof-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/23/business/dbpix-dealprof/dbpix-dealprof-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/23/business/dbpix-dealprof/dbpix-dealprof-articleInline.jpg" id="100000003015584" width="190" height="190" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="190"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Harry Campbell</span></figcaption></figure></div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
The trust is back, baby.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">More than a century ago, a wave of industry consolidation swept through the United States over the course of two decades, a frenzy of deal-making often facilitated by the banker John Pierpont Morgan.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This wave of Gilded Age mergers and acquisitions put together the so-called trusts that controlled the sugar, steel and oil industries, among others. John Moody, who founded the credit ratings agency bearing his name, calculated that during this wave, roughly 5,300 companies were consolidated into just 318 trusts. The consequence was the domination of many industrial sectors by one or more trusts.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Sound familiar?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the past few months, it seems gigantic, industry-consolidating acquisitions are all the rage. Reynolds American recently announced a $27.4 billion acquisition of Lorillard, while <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=TWX&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Time Warner Inc">Time Warner</a> has been approached by 21st Century Fox for a combination in a deal valued at over $80 billion. Similar machinations are occurring in the telecommunications industry, as <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=CMCSA&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Comcast Corporation">Comcast</a> seeks to acquire <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=TWC&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Time Warner Cable Inc">Time Warner Cable</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The online behemoths <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=FB&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Facebook, Inc.">Facebook</a> and <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=GOOGL&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Google Inc.">Google</a>, for their part, are locked in battle by paying billions of dollars for start-ups with lots of potential but no revenue in a bid to dominate the Internet.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Are these the new trusts?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The answer may be yes, unfortunately. Todayâs trusts are eerily similar to those of the Gilded Age, except they seek not quite to eliminate the competition but merely to dominate the market with a few competitors at most.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Those differences are important for the antitrust laws.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">These megacompanies have good reason to rush to grow to enormous size. Todayâs economy requires grand scale in many areas. Size gives these companies the ability to negotiate more ably with each other and meet looming technology threats. The potential round of mergers in the cable and media industry is about obtaining the leverage needed to negotiate cable access fees and deal with new broadcast technology on the Internet.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">These new combinations are also not monopolies. In the case of Reynolds American and Lorillard, the combined company would potentially control 90 percent of the cigarette market in conjunction with its main competitor, <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=MO&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Altria Group Inc">Altria</a>, the maker of Marlboro cigarettes. But that would be a duopoly, with real competition between two behemoths. Reynolds American would also sell some assets to Imperial Tobacco Group of Britain, possibly creating a more competitive player.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A combined Time Warner and 21st Century Fox would control 40 percent of the market for broadcast cable fees, reducing the market to four main players: itself, Comcast, <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=DIS&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Walt Disney Company">Walt Disney</a> and Sumner Redstoneâs <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=CBS&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about CBS Corporation">CBS</a> and <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=VIAB&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Viacom Inc">Viacom</a>. As for cable itself, the two biggest players, Time Warner Cable and Comcast, would control about a third of the market if they succeed in their merger.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The mergers are happening beyond tobacco and media. Among wireless providers, the companies have been working furiously to figure out how to go from four big companies to three. Pharmaceutical companies are also rushing to consolidate, driven in part by drug development needs and in part by tax reasons.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As for banks, well, the financial crisis took care of that. There are now maybe four big banks in the United States â <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=BAC&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Bank of America Corporation">Bank of America</a>, <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=C&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Citigroup Inc">Citigroup</a>, <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=JPM&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about JPMorgan Chase &#038; Company">JPMorgan Chase</a> and <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=WFC&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Wells Fargo &#038; Company">Wells Fargo</a> â who hold about 40 percent of the market for consumer banking. Then there are the airlines, which are now down to four North American carriers that control about 75 percent of the market.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">These companies are not monopolies in the trustbusting sense, but many big industries in the United States are becoming dominated by just a select few.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Because these combinations may not reduce competition in the near term, they are likely to pass muster under antitrust laws originally passed to address the Gilded Age trusts. Under those rules, refined and amended over the past century, companies may merge so long as the combination would not substantially lessen competition.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This standard works to ensure that after the merger, consumers will still have a choice, and that the choice will be real. To be fair, the Obama administration has not been shy about challenging some transactions under this standard. Most prominently, the Justice Department blocked <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=T&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about AT&#038;T Inc">AT&#038;T</a> from acquiring <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=TMUS&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about T-Mobile Us Inc.">T-Mobile</a>, a move that would have shrunk the wireless market to three competitors.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But this test of competition is rooted in notions of how companies competed more than 100 years ago. Even after a merger of Time Warner and 21st Century Fox, there would still be three or four big competitors. Indeed, it may even be that the competition among them for consumers is fierce. This calculus, however, excludes the political and other power that a concentrated industry can wield with government and regulators.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Every industry now has its own Washington-based nonprofit to push its agenda. For wireless it is CTIA, and for cable it is the National Cable &#038; Telecommunications Association. There is even an e-cigarettes group called the Electronic Cigarette Industry Group. The new megacorporations, simply by virtue of their size, can use these organizations to lobby for significant change. And with the political-spending rights given to them by the Supreme Court in the Citizens United decision, these corporations are even more powerful. They are able to steer large sums to preferred candidates. Though they have yet to flex that muscle to the extent that they might, the fear that they could do so is enough to give these companies significant political power with politicians.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">These companies are already using their power to push profits higher. While the recovery of the United States from the financial crisis has been slow, corporate profits are at a record high.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In other words, todayâs outsize mergers are really about power.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This is not to say that size is inherently bad. Big banks, for example, may be necessary for a capital market worth trillions of dollars. Bigger companies may deliver goods more efficiently and have the global scale that small companies lack.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And particular industries may be subject to more scrutiny. The <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/f/federal_communications_commission/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the Federal Communications Commission.">Federal Communications Commission</a>, for example, will not approve the transfer of a broadcast license unless it is in the âpublic interest.â But this standard historically has not dealt with the simple power of size or industries dominated by a select few, focusing instead only on the question of competition.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It may very well be that a combined 21st Century Fox and Time Warner would run afoul of the F.C.C. or antitrust authorities. Certainly <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/m/rupert_murdoch/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Rupert Murdoch.">Rupert Murdoch</a> of Fox has given Time Warner lots of ammunition over the years to plead their case.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But even if this deal and others proceed, right now there is simply no real government ability to review the industry consolidation that is occurring today in which industries become dominated by a handful of major players. Yet it is becoming increasingly apparent that size and industry concentration affect American society even if competition still exists.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The century-old antitrust laws do not seem up to the task. Perhaps it is time to create laws for a new Gilded Age and provide regulators the power to determine if megadeals are truly good for America.</p>
<footer class="story-footer">
    <div class="story-meta">
	<p class="story-print-citation">A version of this article appears in print on 07/23/2014, on page <span itemprop="printSection">B</span><span itemprop="printPage">5</span> of the <span itemprop="printEdition">NewYork</span> edition with the headline: Changing Old Antitrust Thinking for a New Gilded Age.</p>    </div>
</footer>
	</div>
